
It can be extremely interactive. vis-network was designed specifically for this purpose. You can move from a "static picture" to a discovery tool where the graph acts as the navigation for your whole website.
Here is how you can implement a "Click for More Info" feature using your current setup.
1. Update the API to send "hidden" Metadata
First, ensure your graph-db API includes the extra info (like abstracts, years, or h-index) in the JSON it sends to the frontend. vis-network allows you to store custom properties inside each node object that aren't displayed as labels but are accessible when clicked.
2. The JavaScript "Select" Event
You can tell the network object to listen for a selectNode event. When a user clicks, you grab that node's data and display it in a sidebar or a modal.
Updated JavaScript:
code
JavaScript
async function loadGraph(authorId) {
    const response = await fetch(`http://localhost:8000/viz/author-network/${authorId}`);
    const graphData = await response.json();

    const container = document.getElementById('mynetwork');
    
    // We use DataSets so we can update them dynamically
    const nodes = new vis.DataSet(graphData.nodes);
    const edges = new vis.DataSet(graphData.edges);

    const options = {
        nodes: { shape: 'dot', size: 16, font: { size: 12, face: 'Tahoma' } },
        interaction: { hover: true, navigationButtons: true }, // Enables zoom/pan buttons
        physics: { enabled: true, stabilization: { iterations: 200 } }
    };

    const network = new vis.Network(container, { nodes, edges }, options);

    // --- INTERACTIVITY SECTION ---

    network.on("selectNode", function (params) {
        const nodeId = params.nodes[0];
        const clickedNode = nodes.get(nodeId);

        // Logic: What to do when a node is clicked?
        console.log("Clicked on:", clickedNode.label);
        
        // Example: Update a 'Info Sidebar' on your page
        const sidebar = document.getElementById('info-sidebar');
        sidebar.innerHTML = `
            <h3>${clickedNode.group === 'author' ? 'Author Details' : 'Research Work'}</h3>
            <p><strong>Name/Title:</strong> ${clickedNode.label}</p>
            <p><strong>ID:</strong> ${clickedNode.id}</p>
            <hr>
            <p>Here you could fetch and show the abstract or h-index from the node data!</p>
            <button onclick="expandNode('${clickedNode.id}')">Explore this node</button>
        `;
    });
}
3. Take it further: "Infinite Exploration"
The coolest feature you can add to a scholarly graph is Dynamic Expansion.
Instead of reloading the whole page, when a user clicks a node, you fetch that node's neighbors and add them to the existing graph. This lets the user "walk" through the research network.
The "Expand" Function:
code
JavaScript
async function expandNode(newId) {
    // 1. Fetch the network for the NEW node the user just clicked
    const response = await fetch(`http://localhost:8000/viz/author-network/${newId}`);
    const newData = await response.json();

    // 2. Simply 'add' the new nodes and edges. 
    // vis-network automatically ignores duplicates by ID.
    nodes.add(newData.nodes);
    edges.add(newData.edges);
    
    // The graph will physically bounce and grow to show the new connections!
}
4. Added Polish for your CMU Project
To make it look professional:
Color Coding: Use different colors for Authors (e.g., Blue) and Works (e.g., Orange).
Scaling: Make the "Work" nodes bigger if they have a higher citation_count.
Tooltips: Add a title property to the node (e.g., nodes.append({"id": 1, "label": " paper", "title": "Full Abstract appears on hover..."})). vis-network shows this automatically on hover.
Summary: What is possible?
Click to show metadata (Abstracts, years, metrics) in a sidebar.
Click to Expand (Grow the graph dynamically).
Double-click to navigate (Go to a dedicated profile page for that author).
Right-click to filter (Hide all nodes except for a specific topic).
Since your backend is already returning the correct ID prefixes (author_... and work_...), your frontend JavaScript can easily decide which icon or color to show based on the ID string!
